Highlights ► We analyze the problem of sampling of alternatives in discrete choice models. ► Develop a novel method for Multivariate Extreme Value (MEV) models. ► Derive the asymptotic distribution of its estimators and show relative efficiency. ► Use Monte Carlo and real data to illustrate and to study small sample properties. Abstract We propose a methodology to achieve consistency, asymptotic normality and efficiency, while sampling alternatives in Multivariate Extreme Value (MEV) models, extending a previous result for Logit. We illustrate the methodology and study the finite sample properties of the estimators using Monte Carlo experimentation and real data on residential location choice from Lisbon, Portugal. Experiments show that the proposed methodology is practical, that it outperforms the uncorrected model, and that it yields acceptable results, even for relatively small samples of alternatives. The paper finishes with a synthesis and an analysis of the impact, limitations and potential extensions of this research. Keywords Sampling of alternatives MEV GEV models 1 Introduction When the number of alternatives in a choice model is huge, measuring or identifying the attributes is impractical without sampling of alternatives. McFadden (1978) demonstrated that if the model underlying the choice process is Logit, 2 Also known as the Conditional Logit, the Multinomial Logit or MNL, depending on the research area. 2 the consistent estimation under sampling of alternatives can be addressed with a simple correction to the log-likelihood function. Diverse applications of McFadden’s results in sampling of alternatives for Logit models can be found in the literature. Some examples are Parsons and Kealy (1992) and Sermons and Koppelman (2001). However, the Logit assumption is restricting and difficult to sustain when the error terms are correlated among alternatives or when the coefficients are random. These restrictions motivate the need to extend McFadden’s (1978) result to non-Logit models. Advances have been made in regard to the problem of estimation with choice-based samples, which are cases where the full choice-set is available to the researcher but the observations are sampled depending on the choices. First, Manski and Lerman (1977) proposed a consistent but inefficient estimator for non-Logit models. This estimator was used by Cosslett (1981) and by Imbens and Lancaster (1994). Later, Garrow et al. (2005) proposed an efficient estimator for a particular case of the Nested Logit model. Lastly, Bierlaire et al. (2008) proposed a novel estimator that is applicable to MEV models with choice based samples and does not require knowledge of the sampling protocol. Sampling of alternatives in Nested Logit is sometimes addressed using the Independence of Irrelevant Nests (IIN) method (Train, 2009, pp. 80). The IIN method applies McFadden’s (1978) method at the level of the nests. However, because the IIN approach requires drawing all the alternatives that belong to each sampled nest, this method is impractical when the number of alternatives within each nest is very large. To avoid this problem, some authors have applied the IIN approach to nest structures that are not consistent with utility maximization (see, e.g. Train et al., 1987). Another practice for sampling of alternatives with the Nested Logit has been to directly apply McFadden’s results for Logit without any modification. Examples of these types of applications include Berkovec and Rust (1985), Hansen (1987) and Rivera and Tiglao (2005). As we show later, this approach may significantly impact the estimators of the model parameters. Finally, some authors (see, e.g. Lee and Wadell, 2010) have suggested the possibility of addressing sampling of alternatives in Nested Logit models by expanding the components of the choice probability that get truncated because of the sampling. Additionally, analyses have been done on the impact of sampling of alternatives in Logit Mixture models. For example, McConnel and Tseng (2000) and Nerella and Bhat (2004) used Monte Carlo experimentation to study the problem of sampling of alternatives in random coefficients Logit models and found that sampling causes only small changes to parameter estimates. Chen’s et al. (2005) use of Monte Carlo experimentation found that the effects of sampling might be severe in Logit Mixture models that capture correlation among alternatives. Finally, in citing an unpublished paper attributed to Haefen and Jacobsen, Domanski (2009) claimed that the use of the expectation–maximization algorithm (see, e.g., Train, 2009) might result in the consistent estimation of model parameters while sampling of alternatives in random coefficients Logit Mixture model. We propose a methodology to achieve consistency, asymptotic normality and efficiency while sampling alternatives in Multivariate Extreme Value (MEV) models. This methodology is an extension of McFadden’s (1978) result for Logit. The MEV is a family of choice models which includes Logit as well as Nested Logit and Cross-Nested Logit, both of which are closed-form choice models that allow for some level of correlation between alternatives. We illustrate the methodology and study the finite sample properties of the estimators using Monte Carlo experimentation and real data. Experiments show that the proposed methodology is practical, that it outperforms the uncorrected model, and that it yields acceptable results, even for relatively small samples of alternatives. The paper is structured as follows: Section 2 describes McFadden’s result on sampling of alternatives for Logit models. In Section 3, the proposed extension to MEV models is presented. Sections 4 and 5 describe the applications of the proposed method to the Nested and the Cross-Nested Logit models. Sections 6 and 7 illustrate the finite sample properties of the proposed method and its application using a Monte Carlo experiment and real data on residential location choice from Lisbon, Portugal. Section 8 summarizes the main conclusions, implications, and potential extensions of this research. 2 Estimation and sampling of alternatives in Logit models Consider that the random utility Uin , which an agent n retrieves from an alternative i, can be written as the sum of a systematic part V and a random error term ε, as shown in the following equation (1) U in = V in + ε in = V ( x in , β ∗ ) + ε in , where the systematic utility depends on variables x and parameters β ∗. This model was originally derived by Ben-Akiva (1973) as an extension of the Logit, and it was later formalized and shown to be consistent with utility maximization by Williams (1977), Daly and Zachary (1979) and McFadden (1978) using independent proofs. In the Nested Logit, the marginal choice probabilities are written as the product of the conditional probability of choosing each alternative (given that the respective nest is chosen) and the marginal probability of choosing the respective nest. The utility of a nest is defined as the expected-maximum utilities of choosing alternatives that belong to the nest, which is known as the inclusive value (Ben-Akiva and Lerman, 1985). McFadden (1978) showed that the Nested Logit model can be alternatively formulated as a member of the MEV family. The generating function G for a Nested Logit model with M nests is (12) G ( 〈 e V ln 〉 l ∈ C n ; γ ) = ∑ m = 1 M ∑ j ∈ C mn e μ m V jn μ μ m , where γ is the set of scales μm of the nests m, and Cmn is the set of alternatives that belong to the nest m. These hypotheses are studied using Monte Carlo experiments in Section 6. 5 Application of the method to the Cross-Nested Logit The Cross-Nested Logit model is a closed-form discrete choice model that allows for correlation among the random components of the utilities of all alternatives in the choice-set. Similar to the Nested Logit, the Cross-Nested Logit considers a set of nests m. However, in the Cross-Nested Logit the nests are totally exhaustive but not mutually exclusive in the coverage of the alternatives in the choice-set. The correlation structure is defined by the scales and by a non-negative weight αjm representing the degree of belongingness of alternative j to the nest m. The first versions of the Cross-Nested Logit were formulated by Williams (1977) and tested with simulated data by Williams and Ortúzar (1982). Examples of applications of this model and variations of it are found in the works of Small (1987), Vovsha (1999), Vovsha and Bekhor (1998), Bierlaire (2001), and Papola (2004). The Cross-Nested Logit model can be formulated as a member of the MEV family. In general, with M nests, the generating function G that results in the Cross-Nested Logit model is G ( 〈 e V ln 〉 l ∈ C n ; γ ) = ∑ m = 1 M ∑ j ∈ C n α jm e μ m V jn μ μ m , where m are the nests, γ corresponds to the set of scales μm of the nests, and the weights αjm represent the degree of belongingness of alternative j to the nest m. Then, the term ln Gin corresponds to the following expression: ln G in = ln ∑ m = 1 M μ α im e V in ( μ m - 1 ) ∑ j ∈ C n α jm e μ m V jn μ - μ m μ m . As with the Nested Logit, if a sample Dn is drawn from the true choice-set Cn in the Cross-Nested Logit, the only term affected will be the sum of the exponentials B in = ∑ j ∈ C n α jm e μ m V jn , which is now weighed by the terms αjm . Consistency, relative efficiency, and asymptotic normality can then be achieved for the Cross-Nested Logit while sampling of alternatives using the following estimator: B ^ in = ∑ j ∈ D n w jn α jm e μ m V jn . Note that in this case there are various nests m associated with each alternative i, and there is one term Bin for each nest m of the model. In order to reduce the notation, the subscript m will be omitted from Bin . The derivation detailed in Appendix B shows that the expansion factors wjn required in this case are equivalent to those shown in Eq. (14). Finally, the same considerations described for the Nested Logit regarding the implications of being able or unable to re-sample are also valid in the case of the Cross-Nested Logit. 6 Monte Carlo experiment A Monte Carlo experiment was performed to illustrate the application of the proposed method for achieving consistency, efficiency, and asymptotic normality in the case of sampling of alternatives in MEV models. The experiment also studies the finite sample properties of the estimators. We first consider an experiment in which the true model is a Nested Logit and then one in which the true model is a Cross-Nested Logit. In both cases, we analyze the efficacy and efficiency of each method in recovering the true coefficients of each model. 6.1 Nested Logit Fig. 1 summarizes the structure of the Nested Logit model for the Monte Carlo experiment. The true model is a Nested Logit with 1005 alternatives, among which the first 5 belong to one nest (J 1 =5) and the remaining 1000 belong to a second nest (J 2 =1000). We chose this heavily unbalanced scheme to, on the one hand, keep the experiment simple, and on the other, preclude particular cases that may arise because of using fully balanced experiments. The systematic utilities Vin depend upon two variables, x 1 and x 2, which were constructed iid Uniform (−1,1) for the N =2000 observations. The true parameters of the model are μ =1, μ 1 =2, μ 2 =3, β x 1 = β x 2 = 1 . The methodology used to implement the Nested Logit model for Monte Carlo experimentation was performed in several steps. First, the choice probability was calculated replacing the true values of the parameters in Eq. (8). Then, these choice probabilities were used to build a discrete cumulative density function by alternative. Afterward, a random number Uniform (0,1) was generated for each observation. Finally, the chosen alternative was determined as the inverse of the cumulative density function evaluated for each random number. We simulated the choices from the choice probabilities rather than the simulated random utilities because the latter approach showed empirical identification problems for the Nested Logit model (Garrow et al., 2010). The sampling protocol used to draw alternatives Dn from the choice-set Cn in this experiment was stratified importance sampling without replacement by nest. First, the chosen alternative for each observation was included. Non-chosen alternatives were then randomly sampled without replacement by nest to create a total of J ∼ 1 = 5 for the first nest and subsequently J ∼ 2 = 5 , 60 , 500 for the second nest. Based on this protocol, we estimated the model using five different methods. The first method is called Truncated. In this case the set Dn is used to build the term B ^ in , and the expansion factors are considered to be wjn =1. The second method is Pop.Shares. In this case the choice probabilities needed to calculate the expansion factors shown in Eq. (16) are replaced by the population shares of each nest divided by the number of alternatives of each nest. The third method is 1_0. In this case the choice probabilities needed to calculate the expansion factors shown in Eq. (16) are replaced by 1 when the alternative is the chosen one and by 0 otherwise. The fourth method is Iterative. In this case the set Dn is again used to build the term B ^ in , but now the expansion factors wjn are calculated using the iterative procedure described in Section 4.3. Finally, we consider a method termed Re-sampling in which an alternative set D ∼ n is randomly sampled to build the term B ^ in and the expansion factors are calculated as w jn = J m ( j ) J ∼ m ( j ) . The model was generated 100 times, and the estimation methods were applied considering sample of alternatives sizes of J ∼ 2 = 5 , J ∼ 2 = 60 and J ∼ 2 = 500 for the second nest. Table 1 reports the following statistics to assess the efficacy and efficiency of each method in estimating the model coefficients. • Bias: Difference between true value of each coefficient and the average of the respective estimators of the 100 repetitions. A smaller Bias implies better small sample efficacy for recovering the true values of the model. • Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): Square root of the sum of the sampling variance and the square of the bias. A smaller RMSE implies better small sample efficiency of the method. • t-test: Ratio between the bias and the sampling standard deviation of the estimators. This statistic can be used to test the null hypothesis that the mean of the sampling distribution is equal to its respective true value. • Count: Number of times the estimators of the 100 repetitions are within a 75% confidence interval of the respective true value. The interval is constructed using the sampling variance from all the repetitions. This statistic is usually termed the empirical coverage. The larger this statistic is, the better the performance of the method. The closer to 75% this statistic is, the closer its empirical distribution is to its theoretical sampling distribution. For identification purposes the scale of the root was normalized to μ =1 for all the cases. Consequently, only the estimators of β x 1 , β x 2 , μ 1, μ 2 are analyzed in Table 1. Since μ is normalized to its true value, there is no need to change the scale to analyze the bias of the estimators. Table 1 shows that both the Bias and the RMSE shrink as J ∼ 2 grows in all methods analyzed. However, there is a marked difference between the Truncated method and the different versions of the correction methods proposed. In the example analyzed, the Truncated method shows large biases that reach 40% when J ∼ 2 = 500 . When J ∼ 2 = 5 or, 60, the bias increases to between 60% and 160%. Furthermore, only one coefficient has nonzero counts (9), and only when J ∼ 2 = 500 . For all other coefficients and values of J ∼ 2 , the estimators are always outside a 75% confidence interval. The t-test that the mean bias is zero is always rejected with 95% confidence. Finally, the RMSE in the Truncated method is always larger than in the corrected methods proposed. This difference illustrates the importance of correctly addressing the problem of sampling of alternatives in Nested Logit models. Among the methods to address sampling of alternatives in Nested Logit models (Pop.Shares, 1_0, Iterative), the results are mixed depending on the value of J ∼ 2 . However, there are two marked tendencies. The first tendency is that all corrected methods outperform the Truncated method for all values of J ∼ 2 . For J ∼ 2 = 500 , the differences between the Truncated and Resampling and the corrected methods become huge. The second tendency is that the Iterative method is outperformed by the other corrective methods in this experiment. For J ∼ 2 = 5 , the best method is Pop.Shares. The bias of all the estimators is the smallest (although it still goes up to 45%), all the t-tests are below the critical value for 95% confidence and, in terms of the empirical coverage, more than 60% of the time the estimators are within a 75% interval of their true values. The second best method for J ∼ 2 = 5 is Resampling. The biases are slightly larger than those in Pop.Shares, but all t-tests are below the 95% critical value and about 30% of the repetitions are within a 75% confidence interval. While the Iterative method has larger empirical coverage than 1_0, the biases for 1_0 tend to be smaller and fewer t-tests are above the 95% critical value. Finally, regarding the RMSE, results show that 1_0 is relatively more efficient for this experiment. For J ∼ 2 = 60 , Resampling is clearly superior with biases at or below 1%. 1_0 and Pop.Shares also give very reasonable results with biases below 3%. The t-tests are very low among these three methods which implies p-values above 77%. The counts are above 86. This is not the case for the Iterative method, where biases are above 24% and there is only one parameter for which the null hypothesis that it is equal to its true value is accepted with 95% confidence. Regarding efficiency, the RMSE of Pop.Shares and 1_0 are similar and both are markedly lower than that of the Iterative method. Finally, for J ∼ 2 = 500 , all the methods proposed to address sampling of alternatives for this Nested Logit model performed well. Biases were around 3%, p-values were above 87%, empirical counts were very close to the theoretical value, and the RMSE was very small. In summary, the results reported in Table 1 suggest that the Resampling method had relatively better behavior. Additionally, all methods except for Iterative showed an acceptable behavior for J ∼ 2 as low as 60. Even when J ∼ 2 = 500 , the uncorrected model did not work acceptably well. However, these results do not imply that the Resampling method should always be preferred and the Iterative method should be discarded. There are other Monte Carlo experiments for which the iterative method may be equivalent or better. For example, the Cross-Nested Logit experiment described later in Section 6.2 shows the Iterative method to be superior to Resampling. The Monte Carlo results are not a full description of the small sample properties of the estimators. Rather, they are a partial description that is valid only for the examples analyzed and they should be interpreted as an illustration of the behavior of the models. To complement the results reported in Table 1, we report the estimation time attained by each method in Table 2 . The most significant result in this case is that estimation time for Iterative is 10–20 times larger than that of other methods, with small J ∼ 2 , and the ratio goes down to about 3 times when J ∼ 2 = 500 . This result suggests that Iterative has problems of stability when the number of elements used to approximate the logsums is small and also implies that the exploration of alternative optimization procedures may improve the performance of the method. Nevertheless, given that Pop.Shares and 1_0 showed a better performance and are faster and easier to implement when Resampling is not possible, the benefit of exploring potential improvements to Iterative seems questionable. Finally, Fig. 2 provides a graphical and detailed representation of the sampling distribution of the estimators obtained in the Resampling method - the method for addressing sampling of alternatives that worked best for this particular Nested Logit experiment. Fig. 2 shows four plots, one for each estimated parameter β ˆ x 1 , β ˆ x 2 μ ˆ 1 and μ ˆ 2 . The abscissas axis corresponds to different values of J ∼ 2 between 5 and 60. The ordinates axis corresponds to the values of the respective estimator. The black horizontal line in each case represents the true value of the respective parameter. The black large dot represents the average of the estimators obtained for the 100 repetitions, and the gray smaller dots show the estimator obtained for each repetition. Fig. 2 shows that the bias shrinks dramatically for J ∼ 2 as low as 10 similarly across all parameters. Also, the sampling distribution looks agglomerated around the true value with few outliers. For J ∼ 2 = 5 the sampling distribution seems to be the mix of two distributions. One distribution is agglomerated around (or at least close to) the true value, and the other distribution is agglomerated far from the true value. This result can be attributed to the fact that the Nested Logit model is not globally convex (Ben-Akiva and Lerman, 1985). Therefore, finding a global optimum when J ∼ 2 = 5 may be increasingly difficult and may result in suboptimal values of the estimator for some repetitions. This suggests that potential improvements to the optimization procedure used to estimate the Resampling method may allow for much better results with smaller samples. In these experiments we used the L-BFGS-B method coded in the optim routine of the open-source software R (R Development Core Team, 2008). 6.2 Cross-Nested Logit Fig. 3 outlines this experiment. This may also explain why the Iterative procedure worked better than the other methods in the Cross-Nested Logit model (which was not the case in the Nested Logit model). 7 Application to real data This section applies the method proposed for sampling of alternatives and estimation in MEV models using real data. We present a case study corresponding to a residential location choice model among dwellings located in the Portuguese municipalities of Lisbon, Odivelas and Amadora, all of which are at the center of the Lisbon Metropolitan Area (LMA). The data to estimate the model was constructed using two sources. The first source was a small online survey (SOTUR) conducted in 2009 by Martinez et al. (2010) in the LMA. The second source corresponds to a snapshot of the dwellings that were advertised for sale in February 2007 within the municipalities of Lisbon, Odivelas and Amadora (Martinez and Viegas, 2009). The details on the construction of the database by matching both sources can be found in Guevara (2010). The database is composed of 11,501 alternatives, from which only 63 correspond to chosen dwellings. The main descriptive statistics of the database are shown in Table 5 . Dwellings from the Lisbon municipality tend to be more expensive and older than those from Odivelas and Amadora, although the differences are not statistically significant (with 95% confidence). Dwellings from both regions have approximately equal area. However, dwellings from Lisbon are significantly closer, on average, to the workplace of the head-of-the-households of the sample. Table 5 also shows the distribution of household location, classified by income. 51 out of 63 households reside in the Lisbon municipality and the largest share of households in the sample have an income that is between 2000 and 5000 Euros per month (€/M). Using the data described in Table 5, we developed a Nested Logit model that allowed for correlation between alternatives geographically. The structure used is shown in Fig. 3. We considered one nest for the 3483 alternatives that belong to the Municipalities of Odivelas and Amadora. The other 8018 alternatives from the Municipality of Lisbon were considered to belong to the root of this Nested Logit model. The nesting structure used is simple because of the small number of observations available. More interesting structures, such as multilevel nests by area or Cross-Nested Logit, were impossible to estimate. However, the nesting structure used does illustrate the methodology for sampling of alternatives and estimation developed in this research. Furthermore, despite its simplicity, the nesting structure reflects what is observed in the city. The municipalities of Odivelas and Amadora are similar to what Rayle (2008) defined (using a factor-analysis approach) as the Inner Periphery of the central LMA, a sector that has marked differences with Lisbon’s Municipality. Based on this structure, a Nested Logit model was estimated with the assumption that the 11501 alternatives corresponded to the true choice-set. Because this residential location choice model is based on real data, we must correct for endogeneity. Endogeneity is expected to occur because dwellings have certain attributes that are correlated with price but that cannot be measured by the researcher. Examples of these attributes include the quality of the pipes and recent renovations to the dwelling. To correct for price endogeneity we use the control-function method (Heckman, 1978; Petrin and Train, 2002) and consider the average price of similar dwellings within certain geographical thresholds (see, e.g Guevara and Ben-Akiva, 2006, 2012). The application of the correction for endogeneity for this data is described in detail by Guevara (2010). The results of this model (No Sampling) are reported in the second column of Table 6 and again in Table 7 . It should be noted that the signs of the coefficients of the models are as expected. The coefficient of dwelling area ( β ˆ 5 ) is positive, meaning that households prefer larger dwellings. The contrary occurs with dwelling price ( β ˆ 1 ), age ( β ˆ 6 ), and distance to workplace of the head-of-the-household ( β ˆ 4 ), which are perceived negatively. Also, the impact of dwelling price decreases with household income since β ˆ 2 , β ˆ 3 > 0 , but it is negative for all stratum since β ˆ 1 + β ˆ 2 + β ˆ 3 <0. Additionally, note that the estimator of the auxiliary coefficient δ ˆ used to correct for endogeneity is statistically different from zero, which indicates that endogeneity will be present if the control-function correction is not considered (see Guevara, 2010). Finally, the scale of the nest μO - A is statistically different (with 95% confidence) from 1, which implies that the null hypothesis that the choice model is a Logit is rejected. The second experiment uses the same sampling protocol as before, but now with alternatives that were sampled up to make a total of 500 for the Odivelas-Amadora nest and 500 for the root (Lisbon). The results of the models estimated using this sampling protocol are shown in Table 7. As seen in the Monte Carlo experiments, the estimators of the Truncated and of the Iterative models are similar to those of the model without sampling when J ∼ is large. In the case of Table 6 where only 10 alternatives were sampled, the differences in computational costs were huge. These differences in estimation time reflect the significant gains that can be obtained with sampling. The methodological developments of this paper will enable greater benefits in the implementation of spatial choice models with more realistic error structures and also render the development of better tools for policy analysis. 8 Conclusion This article proposes a novel method to obtain consistent, asymptotically normal, and asymptotically efficient estimators (efficient relative to any other estimator using the same sample of alternatives) for the problem of sampling of alternatives in MEV models. Other methods have been proposed in previous literature only for the Logit and Nested Logit models. Regarding the Logit, the method we propose is equal to the procedure proposed by McFadden (1978). In the case of the Nested Logit, our method is applicable to a wider and more realistic set of problems than the existing Independence of Irrelevant Nests (IIN) approach (Train, 2009, pp. 80). Beyond the Logit and Nested Logit, our method is the first attempt to address the problem of sampling of alternatives in MEV models in general. Monte Carlo experiments showed that sampling of alternatives causes a significant bias in the estimators of the model parameters and in the estimated shares. Additionally, the proposed method for correcting the terms that get truncated because of the sampling performed reasonably well, even for relatively small sample sizes. In cases where the researcher has full control of the data and it is possible to obtain an additional sample to expand the sum of the exponentials, the method proposed is easily applicable. When it is not possible to re-sample, the method requires knowledge of the choice probabilities in order to build the expansion factors. In this final case, three approximated practical methods showed reasonably good results. Additional Monte Carlo evidence, which were not reported due to space limitations, suggests that the sample size required to obtain good estimators while sampling alternatives in MEV models depends on the distribution of the data available and cannot be expressed as a percentage of the cardinality of the true choice-set. In general, an appropriate strategy to determine if the size of the sample of alternatives is large enough is to test the stability of the estimators with a different number of alternatives sampled. The application with real data showed that the proposed method to achieve consistency while sampling of alternatives in MEV is practical and may have a significant impact in the design of more sophisticated modeling tools for policy analysis in urban systems. Various lines for future research may be proposed to address the limitations of this study. First, apply the method on larger real databases and other spatial choice models, such as job and firm location, route choice or activity scheduling. Second, assess the full impact of the methodological advances of this research in policy analysis by applying them in the framework of an operational microscopic integrated urban model such as UrbanSim (Waddell et al., 2008). Third, explore the possibility of extending the approach used in this article to the problem of sampling of alternatives in Logit Mixture models. Finally, it would be interesting to perform more extensive Monte Carlo experiments to explore in greater detail the small sample properties of the estimators including: (i) different sampling protocols when re-sampling is possible, particularly when the distribution of the attributes differ by alternative; (ii) other optimization methods specifically designed for the MEV models and; (iii) different configurations of the data. Appendix A A.1 Proof of theorem on sampling of alternatives for MEV models Given that B ^ in is a consistent estimator of Bin , as J ∼ n increases, the Slutsky theorem guarantees that ln f ( B ^ i ( D n ) ) will also be a consistent estimator of ln Gin , because the log and f are continuous. Equivalently, since π(i|Dn ) is continuous in ln Gin , the Slutsky theorem guarantees that π ˆ ( i | D n ) will be a consistent estimator of π(i|Dn ). Finally, McFadden’s consistency results for Logit, shown in Eq. (6), guarantee that the maximization of the quasi-log-likelihood shown in Eq. (10) will result in the consistent estimation of the model parameters as N increases. Note that the claim of McFadden’s consistency result is established as N increases, but the consistency of B ^ in , ln f ( B ^ i ( D n ) ) and π ˆ ( i | D n ) is established as J ∼ n increases. To rely legitimately on the Slutsky theorem, it is essential to determine a concordance between J ∼ n and N. This concordance can be established by analyzing the asymptotic properties of the estimators. The asymptotic distribution of the estimators of the model parameters that result from the maximization of the quasi-log-likelihood shown in Eq (10) can be derived using the two-stage approach employed by Train (2009, pp. 247–257) to analyze the asymptotic properties of simulation-based estimators. In the first stage, we will analyze the asymptotic distribution of the sample average of the score, which is defined as the gradient of the quasi-log-likelihood shown in Eq. (10). In the second stage we will use those results to derive the asymptotic distribution of the estimators of the model parameters. Consider that the choice-sets C and D, of cardinalities J and J ∼ respectively, do not vary across observations, and that there is a single term ln Gn that needs to be approximated for each observation n. coredata.dc:description: Abstract We propose a methodology to achieve consistency, asymptotic normality and efficiency, while sampling alternatives in Multivariate Extreme Value (MEV) models, extending a previous result for Logit. We illustrate the methodology and study the finite sample properties of the estimators using Monte Carlo experimentation and real data on residential location choice from Lisbon, Portugal. Experiments show that the proposed methodology is practical, that it outperforms the uncorrected model, and that it yields acceptable results, even for relatively small samples of alternatives. The paper finishes with a synthesis and an analysis of the impact, limitations and potential extensions of this research.
coredata.dc:title: Sampling of alternatives in Multivariate Extreme Value (MEV) models
